  "prompt": "Business consulting SOW not complete, do we have to pay?",
  "response": "Whether you have to pay for a business consulting Statement of Work (SOW) that is not complete can depend on several factors:\n\n1. **Contractual Obligations**: Review the contract or agreement you have with the consulting firm. It usually outlines payment terms, conditions for completion, and what constitutes completion.\n\n2. **Progress Payments**: If your agreement includes milestones or progress payments, you may only be required to pay for work that has been completed according to the terms laid out in the SOW.\n\n3. **Nature of Services Rendered**: If the consultant provided services that are useful or valuable, you might be obligated to pay for those services, even if the overall project is not complete.\n\n4. **Termination Clauses**: Check if there is a termination clause in your contract that specifies how to handle payments if the project is halted or not completed. \n\n5. **Negotiation**: If the consultant fails to deliver as promised, you might be able to negotiate a reduced payment, a credit toward future services, or even a complete cancellation of fees if there was a breach of contract.\n\n6. **Legal Advice**: If you are unsure, it may be wise to consult with a legal professional who specializes in contract law to understand your rights and obligations.\n\nMake sure to document all communications and agreements related to the SOW and any incomplete work to support your position.",
